A WORD OF CAUTION: Be extra careful playing around with an air hose, etc. - they can kill under the wrong circumstances.

The same goes for any other such type of device involving compressible fluids.

Here's why:

Years ago (before you kids were born) when I was just getting started working, at a nearby furniture manufacturing firm, which inherently has lots of dust from sawing, sanding, etc, some guys were using an air supply line to dust themselves and their clothing off, typical behavior just prior to leaving at the end of their shift.

Somebody thought it was cute to horse around, and stuck an air nozzle up someone's ass while in operation. The result was disastrous. The fellow on the receiving end suffered multiple ruptured intestines, and died within a few minutes because the local hospital was helpless in handling such an emergency.

For those who may think this is a fake post, if interested you should be able to find something about it in the local newspaper. It happened at Berkline Corp in Morristown TN (no longer in business as most such manufacturing has moved overseas) in 1962.

Please be careful when using compressed air or any other compressible fluid devices.

but...vlans do work when you plug them directly into a computer. but you have to have an ip address on the same network as the interface for the router for that network. so if your router interface on that vlan is 10.0.1.1/24 then you will need an address on your ethernet adapter that is in that same range 10.0.1.x/24. that is regardless of whatever the devices has for it's own ip address. for instance a router can have an ip address of 192.168.1.1 with a vlan with an interface 10.0.1.1. but if you have a 192.168.1.x address you are never going to get into the router from that vlan only from direct interface with the router it's self. (so long as whatever port you are plugging into isn't a member of a vlan that you don't have an acceptable IP address for.) the funny thing is if the router is setup properly you can just use the default gateway for the network to interface with it usually regardless of what subnet or vlan you are on.

If your planning on trying to put 10Gbps through an x86 PC/Server running PFSense you need to do a reality check. Those small PC router rigs are not set up with the correct NIC caching or buffering and the PFSense builds are not set up by default to actually offload to your the NIC to actually function properly. This is why you can't purchase a 10Gbps firewall for less than +100K. Commercial firewalls use special ASICs that have firewall DPI capabilities and the ability to offload specific functions to hardware to achieve those sort of throughput requirements. The other thing you need to learn is that most cloud services and hosting platforms work by distributing the load away from a central bottleneck firewall, into smaller edge based firewalls basically just police a single VLAN only to reduce the throughput requirements on the filtering interface. Most PFSense builds struggle to actually forward more than 1Gbps, the ones that are above this tend to come from the PFSense certified hardware / software builds done the dev leads as an additional income stream

I dont understand why clever people like yourselves do not have a vaccum dust collector system installed in your server room, when you have real money it would also help to have slight "low pressure" chamber between the enclosure and the server "room"

In fact given the small size of the old server room you are better off building a plexiglass outside box in the warehouse and the secondary inner glass box that is air-cooled/air-conditioned via the first box. Not knowing how your warehouse looks now I do remember in episodes past that you had space to build a deck. By hermetically sealing the box within another box, you could keep the room relatively dust free, quieter on the outside and save your components that are over cooking because of the dust and heat... you can have a filtration system and thus keep any dust away from the main room servers in part due to the low pressure in the outer chamber. With a pressure seal that results, meaning the dust attraction to the static on the metal boxes can be mitigated if you earth those rails as well. You can have filtered air going into the secondary box from the primary through a second set of microfilters. All modern cars have them and when I was building my own boxes I used to buy an appropriate size from my car spares. this should keep your costs lower for longer and cooler. also being off the floor helps and being a see through box means you can monitor this 24/7/365.

Okay, I totally get that when you have to run a business there isn't always time to do this properly. But when your business is literally depending on this stuff working, you might want to put a little more work into making sure you're doing it right - one day, this is going to fail on them, and because there is zero documentation and it's all chaotic and disorganised it's going to take them days to get it working again. This entire video is basically a list of "don't do this". Also, if you want to make a change like this, for fuck's sake, run it in a lab first! Test that it works before ripping out your old setup - now they are in the position that they have to get it done on time or they're literally not able to get any work done, and that will cost them for every day they spend getting this back instead of doing work. Don't back yourself into a corner like this - just get as much as possible prepared, and be ready to switch back to the old system in case something goes wrong. If I were to do something like this, in my personal system, it's one thing, but they're a business and they need this to work, so this is a terrible example.

The reason the NVR was sagging in the rack is because it was only held in with the top 2 screws on the ears.  When front mounting stuff you should always mount with the bottom screws that way the weight of the device pulls the top in, rather than pushing the bottom out, and it sits right.   Obviously ideally you would use 4 screws, but if you have to use 2, go for the bottom not the top.

It's not true that the vlans dosen't work on computer. Simple way to add in any linux :

:~# vconfig add eth0 888
Added VLAN with VID == 888 to IF :eth0:
~# vconfig add eth0 4
Added VLAN with VID == 4 to IF :eth0:
~# vconfig add eth0 3
Added VLAN with VID == 3 to IF :eth0:
Now you are able to passthrough vlans in trunk to your laptop and they should work perfectly fine.

I believe you could do the same on Windows using some kind of software.

@grey„Ç∞„É¨„Çß "dark fiber" is a marketing term given to the lowest quality of priority sonet access. Sonet has different priorities given to different virtual links, so dark fiber is a WAN service that will be completely unusable when any of the higher priority customers reach high utilization.
Dark fiber is not unused fiber optic lines, its just a way for network providers to make money by selling unused capacity on fiber optic lines that are used to carry sonet virtual links for higher paying customers.
Its basically crap.
Dark fiber is not in itself internet access as your virtual link needs to be terminated at an ISP to use it for internet access (just like any other WAN link technology).
Sonet is a layer 2 protocol like ethernet but sonet is designed for service providers and allows them to set throttle rates, priorities, and other QOS stuff. Sonet uses virtual links so the connection is independent of the physical network links as the sonet connection can be dynamically switched so this makes it more reliable than installing direct fiber optic links. You install a fiber optic link to the providers trunk and your sonet connection is magically switched through the correct links to its destination.
Sonet is intended for use in the links between data centers or other big business offices and is not for residential use. Your residential ISP probably pays for Sonet links for its connection to other regions and its peering providers (that your ISP pays to get internet access) but your home connection using cable internet is DOCSIS (which behaves like an ethernet hub which eventually connects to the ISP miles later so you can use wireshark to see traffic of your neighbors) or DSL (which behaves like a direct ethernet connection over modems).

Run it as a transparent caching proxy for HTTP. But mostly it's good for making it so you don't even have to hit the net for common files like javascript used everywhere (jQuery, etc) or little assets like images and junk that never change and everyone pulls a lot (logos of big sites, etc).

As an IT professional this whole video was just cringe. You need a clear plan for these types of changes, you want to get to a point where when you're executing any change to Production you're just following instructions you put together earlier based on your planning and testing. Yes it takes more time, and yes you're a small company, but when you're risking Production having a clear plan can really save you. When you go in without a proper plan, you make mistakes and when you're tired and stressed you make bigger mistakes. So whilst I think it's unlikely you've had any large impact to your Production due to issues during maintenance and upgrade work you've performed so far, when the day comes that you're working on a Sunday night/ early Monday morning trying to get everything back online ready for start of business hours Monday morning, you'll be wishing you planned and tested properly before hand.

1. Your server room is too small. With all that you are racking you need two racks 1 for servers, 1 for network stuff (patch panels and switches).
2. If you have to dust out the the servers at all then you've got some major issues that need to be addressed ASAP. I have gear in my server room that has been running 24x7 for over 5 years and has nearly zero dust in it.
3. Switching ISP or doing anything that requires changing out racked equipment should NEVER mean having to pull everything apart to do it.

The cables should all be drawn along the sides of the rack, and then pushed in to the switch/patch panel from the sides, just so you can get the surrounding gear above or below out without unplugging everything. Linus, you need a room about 3-5 times the size of what you have and probably 3 racks. 2 for servers and such and one for networking. The server racks should have top-of-rack access switches which are then trunked to a core switch to handle the traffic appropriately. The network rack would have sufficient space for your NVR and security stuff without interfering with the normal flow of servers going in and out. Since you were using new switching anyway, why didn't you pre-configure the router for all the LAN traffic (including switching VLANs) and test that before attempting the install on the production network?

And for all that is holy on this earth, please get a rack console KVM. It's 1U, but you would be rid of that wall-mounted keyboard and monitor monstrosity that you have to hinge upward against the wall to move servers in and out.

‚ÄúWhich means we‚Äôll have much lower level access...?‚Äù What? That whole reasoning makes no sense. Your previous router (from the Ubiquiti EdgeRouter line of products) had command-line programmability, which I assume is what you mean by lower level access. And whether you use the GUI or CLI on an ER, you still can solve 90% of your issues by checking your configuration. There are occasional bugs in firmware, but Ubiquiti is pretty good about rectifying them. Their firmware issues certainly don‚Äôt warrant any negative comments about the overall performance of an ER at up-to 1Gbps WAN links.

The only thing you get by using PFsense is the ability to use hardware actually capable of 10Gbps WAN links. Ubiquiti‚Äôs products support 10Gbps switching, but not 10Gbps routing.

And for anyone that wants to go on about how PFsense can do things like content filtering and other security appliance features, first, I‚Äôm not saying that PFsense can‚Äôt simply that it isn‚Äôt relevant to the conversation because second, CPU bound features things like IPS/IDS, content filtering, etc all negatively affect routing ability. Running security features can mean that your 10Gbps-capable router is now a 9Gbps-capable router.

@Can0n Fodder Actually I wouldn't recommend the Ubiquiti UniFi line. I much prefer the programmability of Ubiquiti's EdgeMax line of products, which don't work with the UniFi controller. Also, EdgeOS has features that just aren't usable because of the dependency on the controller. For example, the EdgeRouter can do time-based firewall rules (say you want to block something from 8 AM to 12 PM). USGs run EdgeOS as their operating system so you can manually program time-based firewall rules, but because of how the controller wipes and rebuilds the config every time it provisions a device, any features you configure that aren't explicitly in the controller will be undone on reboot or on provision. UniFi is still great for wireless though. My number one recommendation for corporate wireless installations.

@Linus Tech Tips First, EdgeOS isn't just "firmware". It's a full-blown OS (Debian Linux to be exact) with built-in routing functionality. More specifically it is a fork of Vyatta, as is the open-source VyOS. EdgeOS and JunOS, Juniper's router OS, are near identical, even down to a lot of command syntax. Also, while the command structure is different, Cisco's NX-OS is the same idea, Linux core with routing functionality built-on top.

Next, EdgeOS allows for CLI commands to be entered from the GUI as well. I agree it's very convenient. DMGESG should exist in the Linux kernal as well, but I am unsure. Tuneables may also exist because well, Linux. OpenVPN runs great on EdgeRouters, though I think there are bandwidth limitations (the best I'm getting on my ER is 10/10 Mbps, which is fine for my needs). Also, all EdgeRouters except the ER-X allow for configuration outside the scope of the GUI.

Lastly, concerning the rest, more logging is just due to the OS differences. pfSense just logs more, which is a great feature. Boxes running pfSense are also much more of a security appliance than any of Ubiquiti's EdgeMax routers. That makes sense given their use case. You don't install an ASR 1000, a Cisco router meant for ISPs, expecting security appliance features. EdgeMax routers are meant for WISPs, though they don't perform badly in enterprise situations where content filtering, email scanning, and other security appliance features aren't a concern.

All-in-all, I think pfSense is a great choice, but I think you should have explained it a bit more clearly. Did you want security features? Did you just want to test something out that you heard was good? Did you not know the feature-set of EdgeOS? Ultimately it doesn't matter. I'm curious more than anything. Regardless, I very much enjoyed the episode and am excited for part 2.

pfSense allows for running console commands and directly editing config files from the webUI, which is a convenience factor; We also gain access to BSD tuneables, to say nothing of things like dmesg to identify hardware faults. More stuff gets logged (which can help with service problems), we aren't tied to vendor-specific implementations of any given service (especially OpenVPN, which is important for us), and while it's not a major concern, if we had a mind to, we could set up services outside of the scope of the GUI since we're running an actual operating system rather than firmware.

Also, the router itself is a Supermicro SuperServer 5019D-FN8TP we got specifically for this project. -AY

As a professional electrician/network installer I am cringing throughout this video.

@Hasooni As an installer there are certain parameters that at a professional level need to be met.
#1 Access. Battery backup systems, hard drives, servers are in their nature heavy items to install. They are constantly fighting with the door to do what they need to do. The room should have been sized to allow the equipment to be serviced in rack and if the equipment isn't designed for in rack servicing then access to the front and rear of the rack should be enough to allow unrestricted lifting and setup of equipment. At the very least they should have propped the door open while removing the equipment. Rule of thumb for me is about 36" minimum on both sides of the rack unless the customer specifies a smaller dimension and even then I would fight it.
#2 Neat installations. This is not just about looking good, but thinking ahead when you do any patching and cable routing. Some servers for example come with modules that may need to be replaced. If you route your cables across the modules you will have to completely unplug your system during maintenance.
#3 Labeling. At no point did I see any labeling, it doesn't even look like they used a proper patch panel to change over from permanent link (field wiring) to the switch. Every wire EXCEPT patch cables from the patch panel to the switch must be labeled. And any sensitive cabling that shouldn't be unplugged should either be a different color or clearly labeled at both ends.
#4 Safety. Drilling metal without proper safety glasses, lifting those heavy hard drives bays without using their legs, carrying the equipment on a cart not designed to hold the weight. Sure those server room carts CAN be used like that but one bad bolt and you are out not just a cart but thousands of dollars of equipment. Just not worth the risk.
#5 Using compressed air and not avoiding static charge. Theres a big difference between using compressed air from a can and air from a tank. The air speed coming out needs to be regulated when blowing out sensitive equipment. If its too high and you blow around circuit boards you can dislodge or break small capacitors in the circuit. Static charge buildup can also be an issue. Anytime you have air running over a surface you can create static charge, sure its minimal and only a freak set of circumstances could lead to damaged components, but if you are dealing with equipment worth more than you are willing to pay to replace then you need to guard against it.
#6 Anytime you are dealing with cataloging or recording parts you do not remove anything until you have the needed space to properly accomplish the task. You get a worktable (which we know they have) set the hard drive enclosure down and then as you remove a hard drive you catalog one at a time. Even if order doesn't matter nothing gets removed until you are ready to jot down part numbers, or Mac addresses when dealing with Wifi systems for example.

Buddy, I hear you... I bought an Intel NUC several months ago to have a personal device at work so I could do personal things on non-company hardware. Talked to support for a week, trying various tweaks and changes, often having to re-install Windows because of the way the Optane module interfaces with the drive the OS is on (long story..). In the end, they sent a new Optane module. The day I installed it, I got two more "MEMORY MANAGEMENT" stop codes. The million dollar question, why does every one shove servers in such tiny rooms. If it was up to me a server room would be at least the size of a bedroom with the rack in the middle to allow for easy access from all sides :) The cost per sq foot of space vs the headache of not having enough space is worth it. Oh and so many companies use server rooms as storage rooms to. The clutter man the clutter. I didn't see that in your server room but so many companies do that.

No no. No one uses their server room as a storage room. Because that would mean you had the servers first and that's just crazy.
It's the other way around. For some bliiiip reason IT equipment comes as an afterthought.

You're correct, however most places don't think about server/equipment placement, except as an afterthought. If they need to house 5-10 employees, they get room for them (If they're lucky), then start figuring out where the equipment will be placed (maybe).  Shove it in a closet? Place it in a cupboard?  Hang it on the wall over an employees desk?  So many places to stash a server that they only care about when it's broken!
@pablo .... That's just a stupid statement. Security starts with room access. Period. Lack of space and tripping over yourself can result in accidents damaging equipment and or personal injury.

@Alec Gregorini I really wonder about that and would like to hear from a expert on this. I know you need a larger AC to cool a larger room. But unlike a house or apartment a server room only has one source of heat unlike a bedroom with Windows. If you have a enclosed room in the middle of the building and the only heat generation is from servers, my question is does the space of the room matter a lot. I would think a larger room would dissipate the heat better thus lower temperature exposure for the server vs a small space that condenses the heat. I would think that the cost difference in cooling would be marginal.The reason I say this is because once the room is cooled it is easier to keep it cool. Either way, I would much prefer having a proper mount of space.
Less cost to cool a smaller space

21:40 "vlans don't work when you plug directly into a computer" Yes they do, computer management >device manager > your NIC > right click, select properties > advanced > VLAN ID > set it to whatever your VLAN is.

@Damian Chili≈Ñski ok, I've never configured any vlans directly on servers (unless vmware hosts) and do all my work on the network side. And yes, definitely should have some mgmt / oob vlan separate from your other front and traffic. In used to working with a much bigger estate, in a sme, maybe but not when dealling with 3000+ servers and 20k clients.
The PfSense co fig in this situation is the most complex part. The network vlans on the switches is the easy bit.

@Lloyd CW using tagged ports to physical machines like servers (maybe not workstations) can be actually handy. It's harder that way to accidentally connect some random machine to eg. DMZ network when you put cable into wrong port in switch. Also all stationary devices should use separate management and WAN vlans if possible. This way it's more flexible and easier to shape mgmt traffic to eg. bypass some security appliances (in order to not overload them with updates traffic). I sometimes use tagged management ports even if there's only 1 vlan on port.

Just because you can do it, doesn't mean you should. That's a horrible way to configure vlans, plus the admin overhead would be horrible. Just set them all to access ports with their default vlans and allow all the vlans you wish to access the router to the uplink trunks. Done.

@Garey Fesz I think all do realistically. Every single NIC I've ever encountered in my entire life does. Including one in raspberry pi and that crappy 4$ chinese usb 2.0 100mbps adapter too... And samsung 10" netbook with first gen Atom does as well.

the way vlans are "trunked" from a router this pfsense and a switch is with ieee 802.1q protocol which basically "tags" the ethernet frames with a vlan number. If a devices interface is not configured to look for the vlan "tags" then,and you send vlan "tagged" frames to it, it will not work. Usually a switch interface can be configured as "access" which means no vlan "tags" or as "trunk" which means it expects frames to be "tagged" with a vlan number. you need to configure one interface on your switch for trunking to be connected to pfsense and the others configured for access. in pfsense you I believe you configure vlan "virtual" interfaces with parent interface as the physical interface. that interface should be connected to the "trunk" interface on the switch.also you need to configure vlans in the switch and assign the access ports that you want on which vlan to that vlan.

13:42 So is spinning the fan on servers with compressed air/vacuum bad? I did that before on my server.....

@Thomas Davis and others, while it's not an absolute, most of the FETs (and similar) used to drive and sort of motor will have what's called a flyback diode built in to them. they need this to keep from blowing up when they turn off power to the fan, which they do thousands of times a second.

The only cases where I can see any damage from spinning a fan with air would be from over spinning, where it wears the bearings or exceeds the back EMF rating of the driver... which is unlikely on a high RPM server blower, or if the fan uses an electromagnetic bearing that needs power to 'hover' the armature... also unlikely in a server.
Long story short, it won't hurt anything.
@Thanny They already sound like the turbine fans on a jet engine at startup... lol
@Zach M I wonder if board manufactures put diodes in the fan circuits...
Not if it's a slow rpm, high rpm will generate a charge and backfeed

It depends on the fan. A fan with bearings rated for a specific RPM being forcefully spun faster by a jet of air might damage those bearings.

Server fans tend to be high RPM units already, so it's unlikely a blast of air will spin them faster than they are rated to go.

But as a whole, it's better to immobilize the fan first.
VLANS do work when you plug directly into a computer, you have to have windows pro and a NIC that supports VLAN tagging so you can tag the Ethernet interface with the correct VLAN ID.

As someone who does this type of thing for a living - Brady labels and velcro are your friend.

Label every cable - network and power. Each network label should have Switch and port, and then destination server / device and port.

Resilience is also your friend - everything has the right to fail at some point - so resilient power feeds to the rack, devices with redundant power supplies as mandatory options (or paired devices in the case where they only have a single PSU).

Colour code your patch leads - come up with a scheme and stick to it - the difference in costs between standard grey and other colours is minimal and makes a hell of a difference.

Dell PowerConnect switches need to have the vlan info configured into them especially brand new out of the box. If it's just a new switch being added to a preexisting stack you can just copy over the config info and be fairly ready to go aside from having to configure a few vlans on a port by port basis depending on the number of vlans each port/device needs to see. Learn the tagged / untagged terminology as well as access, trunk, and general modes. I stole this info from another person on the internet but it's super helpful info if you plan on doing any dell switch programming yourself.

"Access port strictly accepts untagged packets (no vlan info) from the device connected and adds a vlan tag to the incoming packet to be processed in the switch/router. Any packet destined for the device connected to the port will have its vlan info removed. So the port would be considered an untagged member of vlan



Trunk port strictly accepts tagged packets. If the port is a tagged member of a vlan it allow that traffic to pass.



General mode is a hybrid, it allows both worlds to happen. You can add the port to any vlan as a tagged member and it will pass that traffic tagged to and from the port. But you also get the ability to have the port be an untagged member of 1 vlan which it can pass traffic to and from untagged. This is controlled by setting the PVID value for the port.



In my experience you end up using most ports as just straight access or trunk mode. I typically only use general mode when i am talking to a goofy device that is passing tagged and untagged traffic on the same link. Or in a more modern scenario if you have a VOIP phone and computer sharing the same port a general mode port can come in quite handy."

Hey, Serious question for you guys: How well did you actually get 10 Gig routing working on that pfsense box, and how did you manage it if you did get 10Gig? In my experience, the CPU load on a router (that uses a general purpose CPU instead of an ASIC) means that you can rarely get more than a 2-3 Gigs of throughput, even with static rules to bypass some of the packet processing logic.

@Robert Hollar I'm also running the pfsense with lacp enabled on my 2 broadcom nics for want and 4 Intel like also with link agregation. I'm also using the older cards with em driver to reduce the PPPOE single thread problem.

I have done some test with a a pppoe server and a fiew different clients and on Linux with a single Ethernet with a couple load of 6/7% I achieve more or less 1gbps. ( The cable was quite shitty so it was 900 Mbps + something.)


The same setup with pfsense I got a throughput of around 400mbps with 2 core at 100% more or less stuck with network interrupts. I also tried the deferred option and I got only a fiew more Mbps.

The client was running on a Q1900M with 2 gigs of ram.

I also having some really strange problems with my VOIP trunks. Both the pfsense guys and FreePBX guys have no idea on what the problem is.

The UDP connection just drop after 30 second. But this happened only on one trunk the other work fine. (The first that goes up is the only one that have problems).

The real deal would be make a web ui on vyos and add all the functions that has been added on the edger outer series in those years back on vyatta.

@TuttoCrafting Its how linux handles packet forwarding vs freeBSD. Even the PFsense people understand that Netgate, the people that bought PFsense are moving to a product they label as TNSR. It incorporates Cisco's VPP and many other features, ontop of cough linux... or FD.io. I personally don't run PFsense how people have it traditionally set up with a nic for wan, lan, ect... That is a complete waste of resources and lowers overall throughput. Even when I was using Pfsense/opnsese I would lag/bind interfaces together and run a VLan trunk to the switch form the router. This not only increase the theoretical throughput to the router, but also allows the router to continue its job in the case of a link failure. It's a modified version of the age old idea of router on a stick. The problem comes from Freebsd's lack of ability to support more bandwidth that 10G, that's why I moved to Vyos. On a side note if you have a quanta or another switch that isn't cisco... it prob runs a linux backend for switching speeds.

@Linckel this is Enterprise stuff. It gets much worse for any fortune 1000 company with satellite, distributed Warehouses, geographic offices, and tens of thousands of users :-). This video is Enterprise 101 with switches, VLANs, DHCP for assigning network addresses and the shitty job of moving stuff. Linus lucked out too with the disk array. Some require the disk order to be the same to boot :-). If you want to learn more you need to get more experience with projects like this If you want to go into IT

@Timothy Gibney Thanks man, the explanation definitely helped. The problem is that I thought I was a bit more knowledgeable in that thing, since I do related stuff at my school, just a little reality slap there for me.

@Linckel Enterprise networking is not home WiFi by a Longshot. FYI a VLAN is a virtual local area network which means you can setup a different network config for each VLAN or virtual lan. This is for having a different network config for desktops, servers, cameras, and phones etc. For example you may want a DHCP network for a PC but a static manual ip for a server etc. What the thread is talking about is CPU processing for the loads. A Xeon is fast for general needs but each piece of data aka packet needs to be routed and firewalled. 10 gigs a second multipled for each port with rules for each packet is HUGE! Asic are specialized chips for processing data packets and rule logic for firewalls to offload from the Xeons. So now you know the debate on here is about. I hope that helps :-)

Why wasn't the new router configured beforehand?

Switching from one base to another can be a pain in the neck, but you could've virtualized the software for pfsense ... I use opnsense which is a fork of pfsense, and I used pfsense pretty adamantly for a couple of years until I found opnsense to be a bit more secure and easier to use. You could definitely switch to it and use the same configuration too... but I would suggest testing it first.

I saw a lot of things that your team could have organized a little bit better in terms of the whole procedure, I'll give you a pass on the appearance of the overall building as it's pretty common in this line of work to have stuff all over the place. In fact I think that the back room is looking better and better during each video you showcase it. But after what I saw, this begs the question... Why have 5 guys there on the weekend working on this stuff in tandem? You've got a lot of virtualization potential there, you can use a tool that helps meets your performance expectations and then V2P that configuration...

Just some things I saw. Obviously the hardware needs some better dust filters on them, but I imagine that you guys go into that closet quite a bit because I remember when you restored the server room not that long ago... I would suggest keeping that door locked a bit more often and reducing the number of people that can go in there. If you have problems with the network often enough to warrant going in there, I would suggest doing more with the router, as you suggested. Ubiquity is nice and all, but nothing beats FreeBSD IMO. When it comes to Ubiquity, it's great for easily setting up a network that works and is very reliable, but when it comes to consoling into it directly, you have to be pretty good with 'knowing' the commands... what I'm saying is that it's a pain in the ass to console into if you need to do something with the firmware. Whether you use pfsense or opnsense, both options are really better IMO... and because of how sophisticated your network appears, I think you guys made the right choice to drop the Ubiquity. Not saying Ubiquity is bad either, but when it comes to being able to know that it's not a firmware issue, or having a multitude of advanced features that you can define and fine tune yourself, Ubiquity has been less desirable on my part.

Might I suggest getting a shorter rack? Maybe something with wheels so that you don't have to worry about dropping the $20,000 servers? If you guys are really having issues with the network, whether it's vlanning or subnetting, vpns, etc... Might be able to help if the community doesn't have the answers you're looking for.

BTW, your web site is showing up as not secure. You also have some of the staff names bleeding into their titles... probably a css goof somewhere. I don't know his name but the guy that was configuring the router, I would suggest that if he's your current goto IT guy, perhaps give him some more labs so that he can do this type of work without having to shut down the office.

You should've easily been able to replicate the settings you needed over to the new device and swapped it in in about 5 minutes tops. I realize that's a bit of a ballsy thing to say, but having this stuff on lock comes down to config testing.

Yours Truly,
Michael C.

Also, I just would like to add that I'm not trying to sound insulting at all, so if that's the message you heard, that wasn't my intention. It was a closely guarded compliment, I watch you guys a lot and I think you guys do great work. I like the dramaturgy that Linus uses, and I think that Tech Linked is a great idea to continue improving on. Riley is a silly bastard, always LOL'ing at his silly ass remarks... lol again.

Hi linus

As for the Dell switch, you will define the VLAN membership on the VLAN interface instead of the port interface. So go into 'int vlan N' and then type 'tagged te1/x,1/y'  etc. If you want a port to be an access port on only one VLAN, go into the int vlan and type 'untagged te1/x' with the appropriate port number. Port interfaces can be configured to support one untagged VLAN and more than one tagged VLAN also, if desired. Hope that helps.

Or you simply use linux machines and configure vlan in liunx. Windows 7 was supporting VLAN on my Intel NIC, but not anymore with Windows 10 drivers.
As you may need tagged AND untaged traffic on one port and you don't had access to the network documentation you'll struggle to replan the network.

5:06 Guys safety should always be #1 priority :)

Is cleaning with compressed air allowed by law?

In many Canadian jurisdictions, cleaning with compressed air is not allowed by law. Alberta, Newfoundland, Prince Edward Island, Quebec, and Saskatchewan specifically mention that compressed air shall not be used to clean clothes, or in other situations cleaning a person, machinery, work benches, etc. Reference to cleaning may also be included with specific mention to it being prohibited when there is a risk to the worker being injured or that the device must be specifically designed to safely clean a person or surface (federal regulations, Ontario, British Columbia, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, North West Territories, Nunavut, and the Yukon).

On rare occasions, some of the compressed air can enter the blood stream through a break in the skin or a body opening. An air bubble in the blood stream is known medically as an embolism, a dangerous medical condition in which a blood vessel is blocked, in this case, by an air bubble. An embolism of an artery can cause coma, paralysis or death depending upon its size, duration and location. While air embolisms are usually associated with incorrect diving procedures, they are possible with compressed air due to high pressures. While this seems improbable, the consequences of even a small quantity of air or other gas in the blood can quickly be fatal.

https://www.ccohs.ca/oshanswers/safety_haz/compressed_air.html

You need to trunk/tag the VLANs on both the pfSense port connected to the switch, and the corresponding switch port on the Dell. I've never interacted with a Dell switch, but I'd expect it to be notated as tagged or untagged ports. Client ports should be untagged on the client VLAN, and ports that go between VLAN-aware devices should generally be tagged with the required VLAN IDs. Also, for testing purposes, you can configure a Windows NIC to tag a certain VLAN in the properties so it can communicate properly. You don't want to have to do that as a general practice, but during setup it might help.

Of all the hardware I've run into Cisco is the one who doesn't follow the standard tag/un-tagged VLANs.  They have the market share to not care.
Dell is probably a rebranded hp switch. They do rebranded Aruba for wireless controllers so more than likely hp.
Btw macOS support VLAN natively. Might try that too. (If I recall correctly, Windows VLAN tagging in properties is depend on NIC's driver)
